Title : Edward Hoare (cricketer)
Text : {{Use dmy dates|date=February 2016}}
{{Use British English|date=February 2016}}
'''Edward Hoare''' (5 June 1812 â€“ 7 July 1894) was an English [[cricket]]er with [[Amateur status in first-class cricket|possibly amateur status]] who was active in 1831. He was born in [[Hampstead]], London and died in [[Tunbridge Wells]], Kent. He played one [[first-class cricket|first-class]] match for [[Cambridge University Cricket Club|Cambridge University]] on 5th July 1831 against the Cambridge Town Club as an unknown [[handedness]] [[batting (cricket)|batsman]] whose [[bowling (cricket)|bowling style]] is unknown.  He scored three [[run (cricket)|runs]] with a highest score of 3 and took no [[wicket]]s.<ref name="CA36">{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/37/37002/37002.html |publisher=''CricketArchive'' |title=Edward Hoare |accessdate=26 April 2014}}</ref>

A member of the [[C. Hoare & Co|Hoare banking family]], he was also the nephew of the prison reformer [[Elizabeth Fry]], who was his mother's sister.<ref name="timesobit">{{cite news| title = Obituary | newspaper = The Times |issue = 34311 | page = 9 | location = London | date = 9 July 1894}}</ref> He was educated at [[Trinity College, Cambridge]].<ref>{{acad |id=HR830E |name=Hoare, Edward}}</ref> He graduated from [[Cambridge University]] in 1834 as the fifth [[Wrangler (University of Cambridge)|Wrangler]] and became a clergyman; he was a prominent member of the [[evangelicalism|evangelical wing]] of the [[Church of England]] and wrote several books on religious themes.<ref name="timesobit"/> From 1853 he was [[vicar]] of [[Trinity Theatre|Holy Trinity Church]], Tunbridge Wells and an honorary [[Canon (priest)|canon]] of [[Canterbury Cathedral]].<ref name="timesobit"/>

[[Edward Brodie Hoare]], [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Hampstead (UK Parliament constituency)|Hampstead]], was his son.

